  <div id="tribute-info">
    <ul> 
      <h2 id="headline"> The life of J.R.R. Tolkien's writings</h2>
      <li><u>1892</u>- Born on January 3 in Bloemfontein, Orange Free State (now a part of South Africa)</li>
      <li><u>1907</u>- Invents his own language, "Naffarin", based off of Latin and Spanish</li>
      <li><u>1914</u>- Writes his first identifiable "Middle- Earth" fragment ‘The Voyage of Éarendel the Evening Star’</li>
      <li><u>1930</u>- The first line of The Hobbit may have been written.</li>
      <li><u>1937</u>- "Beowulf: <i>The Monsters and the Critics</i>" is published. Later in the year, "The Hobbit" is published. Tolkien was urged by Stanley Unwin to write a sequel, resulting in the writing of "Lord of the Rings". </li>
      <li><u>1947</u>-<i> On Fairy-Stories</i> is published in Essays Presented to Charles Williams.</li>
      <li><u>1949</u>- <i>Farmer Giles of Ham</i> is published.</li>
      <li><u>1953</u>-	Publication of <i>The Homecoming of Beorhtnoth Beorhthelm’s Son</i>.</li>
      <li><u>1954</u>- Publications of both <i>The Fellowship of the Ring</i> and <i>The Two Towers</i>. </li>
      <li><u>1955</u>- Publication of <i>The Return of the King</i>, the final part of the <i>Lord of the Rings</i> trilogy.</li>
      <li><u>1962</u>- <i>The Adventures of Tom Bombadil</i> is published.</li>
      <li><u>1963</u>- Tolkien’s lecture English and Welsh is published.</li>
      <li><u>1964</u>- <i>Tree and Leaf</i> is published.</li>
      <li><u>1966</u>- Publication of <i>The Tolkien Reader</i>.</li>
      <li><u>1967</u><i>- Smith of Wootton Major</i> is published.</li>
      <li><u>1968</u>- 	The BBC broadcasts an 8-part half-hour radio dramatisation of <i>The Hobbit</i>.</li>
      <li><u>1973</u>- Tolkien dies. His son Christopher later finds manuscripts and edits them to be pulished. Titles include:<i>Bilbo's Last Song, The Simarillion, Unfinished Tales of Númenor and Middle-earth</i>, and nine volumes of <i>The History of Middle Earth</i>.</li>
    </ul>        
        <p> Tolkien's work is still being published today and his son, Christopher, continues to edit his father's work. His writings will live forever in the hearts of his fans, readers and movie-watchers alike.<p>
    <h3> “In a hole in the ground there lived a hobbit"- First Line of <i>The Hobbit</i>, where it all began...</h3>
    <h4>To find out more about this fascinating author, visit <a id="tribute-link" href="https://www.tolkiensociety.org/author/timeline/" target="_blank" >this site</a> and read on!
      
